{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503796"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:07:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:07:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2080"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2080"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.02,0.05,0.84,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2080"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44769"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2080"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2080"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29642"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"182"},{"type":"contributions","id":"185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39521"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44769","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44769"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner after tripping and falling whilst walking to the toilet in the dark last night. She has no history of falls, and denies any loss of consciousness or serious injuries sustained from the fall. She has a history of previous myocardial infarction two years ago, hypertension, and insomnia. Her medications list includes furosemide, metoprolol XR and perindopril. She has also recently been started on a short term medication for insomnia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe expresses concern about fracturing her hip from one of her falls. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"What is the most appropriate investigation to assess her risk of future fractures?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Electrolytes, urea and creatinine (EUC)","Complete blood examination (CBE)","Plain X-ray of hip","Dual energy X-ray absorptiometry (DEXA)","Vitamin D Levels"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with specific concerns regarding injuries from further falls. A minimal trauma fracture is a key concern in this age group. As she is 75 years old, according to Australian guidelines this patient qualifies for a bone densitometry to assess for osteoporosis and fracture risk. \u003Cstrong\u003EDual energy X-ray absorptiometry\u003C/strong\u003E (DEXA) scans are the gold standard diagnostic tool for both osteopaenia and osteoporosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the absence of injury, a plain hip X-ray is unlikely to provide information of clinical value. Vitamin D levels are an important risk factor for osteoporosis and are valuable in directing management if diagnosed. With a clear history of a mechanical fall with no loss of consciousness, further investigations into the aetiology of her fall (e.g. CBE, EUC) are not always required.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The DEXA scan is the key investigation in the assessment of a minimal trauma fracture in an older patient."],"references":["Jeremiah MP, Unwin BK, Greenawald MH, Casiano VE. Diagnosis and Management of Osteoporosis. Am Fam Physician. 2015 Aug 15;92(4):261-8. PMID: 26280231."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29642"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2080"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29642","lin